text:
rising: kindred spirit (7/14) by nicholas jones, 26 september 2018. -

kindred spirit - can’t you see that i’m laying in your bed,
after spending my whole saturday
running through your head,
you can feel me underneath you and i can feel you deep inside,
kindred spirit - can’t you see that you don’t have to hide from me?

our views of the world have been defined by billions of years,
of evolutionary theory that brought us here,
together - hand in hand - we stand up in defense,
of everything the world has to use against us,

kindred spirit - can’t you see there are no wars to be waged,
that if we can bring two worlds together then we could motivate,
the change we want to see into the actions,
we want to be defined by - but only when kindred spirits learn to fly together. -

text:
rising: lana del rey (8/14) by nicholas jones, 02 october 2018. -

i always listen to bob dylan when i want to feel close to my father,
blood on the tracks - highway 61 - blonde on blonde,
i don’t know all of the words to every song that comes on,
but i do know just enough to be able to sing along,

i always listen to mariah carey when i miss my ex-boyfriend,
all that glitters is gold - he used to say to me,
and i took that spiritually - as if he was going to say,
that whenever i felt lonely - he was never too far away,

i always listen to madonna whenever i feel like i just want to dance,
because if you’ve hung up your dancing shoes - you’ll never have the chance,
to see the world the way it was meant to be seen - a chance to reinvent yourself each day,
and that everyday is a holiday if you open your heart - at the expense of loving someone else,

i listen to maya angelou on repetition - to soothe,
to heal and redirect my attitude towards the human condition,
you are beautiful and you are strong - and if you have faith,
your wings will spread from to sea to sea - wall to wall - face to face,

and i listen to lana del rey all the time - happy or sad,
to remember what i’ve always wanted and what i once had,
because if we’re only born to die - doesn’t it make sense to cling to life,
with someone who you love - who loves you - while you pass the time. -

text:
let's talk recovery. a large part of me has always been frightened by what recovery would look like. one, i was resistant to the idea of needing medication. and, two, i was afraid it would take my personality away. i would be boring, i guess. well, i'm beginning to enter recovery as i am no longer resistant to taking medication  but embracing treatment, four months strong, a new record of consistency for me. and, it's not that recovery takes away your personality but it stabalizes you. it makes things clearer, decisions easier, and puts things in perspective. i think i might like recovery. recovery from all the intertwined obstacles and mental disorders i face might actually be a relief, a breath of fresh air. i share this incredibly personal story to say, don't stand in the way of your own treatment and your own recovery. look honestly at what's holding you back and accept the role you play. it's hard but that's what makes it worth it. .
.
.

text:
new theatre show offers powerful message in a #metoo era

the one-woman show is a story of empowerment through trauma.
👇👇👇👇👇👇
a new one-woman play is set to shake up london’s contemporary theatre scene this festive season. i’m a woman will take to the stage at the playground theatre this december, with actress ana daud taking the solo role.

i'm woman theatre show offers powerful message
named only as “woman” throughout the play, daud will relive her own traumatic and influential experiences that have shaped her progression to adulthood. following a sexual assault by her drama teacher, the story explores the recovery from a turbulent journey of anorexia, addiction, abortion, and prostitution. haunted by feelings of shame, a continuing battle with childhood traumas and adulthood challenges leaves her vulnerable to a number of taboos and socially-prohibited experiences, as she tries to find meaning and acceptance.
i’m a woman explores how releasing herself from the shackles of the past opened up a new path of love and forgiveness. now a prominent actress, her ability to convey sensitivity, passion and trauma has earned her high praise from many in the industry. her commitment to raising awareness of women’s issues has also been commended.
🎬🎬🎬🎬🎬🎬
with the #metoo movement continuing to gather global momentum, this progressive and timely production gives an insight into how through facing her fears, confronting pain and embracing flaws, daud has emerged feeling stronger than ever before.

this deeply personal yet hugely relatable message is sure to strike a chord in women everywhere.
🇲🇩🇬🇧🇲🇩🇬🇧🇲🇩🇬🇧🇲🇩🇬🇧
directed by dumitru akrish and with inspiration from the bible, this hard-hitting true story merges facts, powerful memories and even notes of humour to explore the truth and ramifications of abruptly losing one’s childhood innocence.

as a prominent contemporary theatre director, akrish has become famous for his ability to take audiences on inspirational and even humorous journeys over the past six years.

the show runs from wednesday 19th december until friday 21st december with each show starting at 7.30pm.

text:
when @jillsoloway’s parent came out as transgender in 2012, they immediately knew art would help them process the news. what they didn’t know was not only would the resulting project, @transparentamazon, win multiple emmys and golden globes, but that they would go on a journey exploring their own gender, eventually identifying as nonbinary – neither male nor female. soloway, who is currently on a tour promoting their new memoir, “she wants it: desire, power, and toppling the patriarchy,” talked to @thelilynews about several themes of their book, including consent, ambition, gender identity and the #metoo movement.
•
soloway says they came to an interesting revelation on their path to identifying as nonbinary: "it’s so weird because i’ve come to the end of this journey by going, 'well, i’m nonbinary so that must be why i felt all this gender trouble,' but then i talk to women and a lot of them feel the same way. why do i have to get dressed up this way? how come when i’m being photographed i have to wear a full face of makeup? what is it about being a powerful woman that means holding your stomach in with spanx while powerful men can let their belly out? these things are gendered ways of moving through the world where women have to take up less space so men can take up more space. they’re really problematic for lots of women — not just women on their way to becoming nonbinary." read the full interview on thelily.com. (photo by presley ann / getty; illustration by @thelilynews)

text: rainn is the nation’s largest anti-sexual violence organization.  they operate the national sexual assault hotline which offers support for those who are victims of sexual assault.  they provide survivors with someone to talk to if they are too afraid to go to authorities or talk tot heir friends.  being able to talk about one’s situation is a very big step in the healing process.  they also offer many more resources relating to sexual assault on their website.  president of rainn, scott berkowitz, when talking about the brett kavanaugh hearing, said “history shows us that when high-profile allegations such as these are in the news it often causes others to reach out too.” this shows how much survivors speaking out effects others and gives them the confidence to speak up too.  #endsexualassault #speakup #metoo

text:
غلام امانی امانی 
اعتراض علیه آزار جنسی اعضای تیم ملی فوتبال بانوان افغانستان 
این اعتراض به هدف دادخواهی و حمایت از زنان ورزشکار عضو تیم ملی فوتبال بانوان کشور راه اندازی شده است. این زنان اکنون تابوی سکوت در برابر تبعیض و سوءرفتار جنسی را شکسته اند و رفتار شرم آور بعضی از مقامات مرد فدراسیون فوتبال به شمول رییس فدراسیون فوتبال کشور را در رسانه ها افشا کرده اند. تعرض و تجاوز جنسی علیه زنانی که از تابوهای سنتی عبور کرده نهایت بی شرمی، فساد و فقدان حاکمیت قانون را نشان می دهد. این مسأله نشان داد که هنوز ورزش برای زنان خطرناک و پرچالش و آسیب زننده است و لازم است علیه این وضعیت بایستیم و اعتراض کنیم. 
ما باید هزینه بی احترامی به زنان و تعرض جنسی به آن ها را افزایش بدهیم و حکومت را در برابر این وضعیت پاسخگو بسازیم. این کار بدون این که همه با همبستگی کامل کنار هم بایستیم، ممکن نیست. از تمام شما دعوت می کنیم تا در حمایت از زنان ورزشکار و حقوق اولیه ی زنان افغانستان کنار ما بایستید و اعتراض کنید. 
در این اعتراض از هشتگ #metoo  و #metooafghanistn در شبکه های مجازی استفاده کنید.

text:
today was a big learning day 🙌 
about a month ago i was encouraged to race at the masters “last chance” meet in order to get @mastersswimming top 10 ranking times before the end of the year. i wasn’t sure i wanted to do that again but i entered. i have not trained like i used to, only a couple of times a week....so no expectations were there...just swim...have fun and try to enjoy doing something that i spent my entire life pursuing. i raced, i laughed, i learned to relax, live in the moment, be ok with “my times” (which were super slow) and just treat the entire 2 days like one giant swim practice 😂🎉💥 13 races, 13 medals, relay races, new friends, almost missing 2 of my swims 😂and finishing the meet with 0 best times...but i am #grateful cuz i realized i still love 💗 this sport even though it has given more heart ache, disappointment, politics and #metoo moments in my young coaching career to ever want to go back 😢 but today i feel proud. proud of my relentless commitment to the pursuit of being my best and always aiming to work for my dream of competing in the olympics. i gave 8 quadrennials (32 years) of my life to this sport including hard work, blood-sweat-tears, sacrifice, dedication of body, spirit and soul and i didn’t “make it” 🙀 but what i did do today was finally realize that what i did accomplish over the past 32 years was freaking amazing 💥💪💦 and that i would give anything to swim my best times again 😌...i learned that it’s ok to want and to love something and not get it....it’s the same in life and it’s the same with people. you can give and love with all of your heart and not get what you want. 🤷🏼‍♀️as long as you are happy with you and what you believe in, you will be ok. so i say this to me and to anyone pursuing a dream or going through doubts or heartache, depression or uncertainty...you are great, beautiful, courageous and a fighter. 
you be you and it will all be ok ❤️🤗💦 .
.
.
.
#swimming #swim4life #swim #youbeyou #proud #southflorida #neolifeathlete #love #mysport #bestsport #lifeiswhatyoumakeit #smile #privateswimlessons #happy #coach #coaching #bebrave 💧

text:
sharing. forgiving. healing.❤️
.
. 
our beyouty unleashed motto is “transparency breeds healing” your story can be the key to unlock someone else’s prison. we are coming together to free each other. we are our sister’s keeper.
.
. 
we have created this space for women to come together to deal and heal. we want you to know that you are not alone in anything that you are going through. come and release what you've been holding on to for so long. it's time to let it go, it's time to heal, it's time to be free.
.
. 
join us in ocoee, fl on saturday, january 5, 2019.  tickets are on sale now for $10 until december 31, 2018. .
. 
if you can't join us, please pray for us. :-) this event is for women who just need a break, a little me-time, and/or a mini woo-sah. we share, we laugh, we cry, we forgive, we heal, we eat, and just have a good ole’ time.
.
.

text:
“now, i will let the children play outside more as they have enough warm clothes.” aliona juric

during the winter season, mwb’s gifts of warm shoes, socks, coats, blankets, and firewood bring immense relief to families living in poverty in moldova. fear and anxiety are replaced with joy, relief, and a sense of being loved, thanks to mwb’s supporters. now the juric family and many like them can enjoy a warm and happy winter despite all the challenges they face.

text:
today marks the one year anniversary of the toronto metoo march, which i feel infinitely blessed to have been apart of, along with hundreds of other survivors of assault and abuse. i am forever grateful to hero leader @_alatheacaroline_ for making this life changing day happen, and for all of the astoundingly brave human beings who came out to participate and support a cause that is at the epicenter of my heart. that day we were no longer victims. we were champions.
the event was one of the most beautifully heartbreaking days of my entire life. i cried tears of pain, joy, sorrow, anger, and love for what we were fighting for then, and i am again right now. although this topic covers so many complex and diverse issues, it can be understood simply as an overwhelming fight for freedom.
and even though we have come a long way, the fight is far from being over. there is so much work left to be done and i am not waiting around for someone to stand up and do something. instead i am brimming with excitement to be continuing this movement, and will be coordinating a feminist artist workshop to unite la artists in solidarity for gender equality. we all deserve to live and create art in a city where freedom from sexual harassment and assault is not the exception, but the rule. there will be a luncheon during the first week of january to kick things off and i welcome you to join me. let’s start talking and get moving. let’s empower each other with our own stories of strength, courage and hope to discuss how we can work together to make la a city that thrives off of equality. this is only the beginning of the most magical era of our lifetime and i am ecstatic to be apart of it. there is no better time to be alive than right now. 
#metoo #metoomovement #equality

text:
yesterday, on my way to #ballet class, i got a little shocked when i looked up from my phone and saw an erected penis pointing at my face. i pretended not to be fazed, left the train at the nearest station and then switched to a different compartment. when i got off the train, the flasher also came out from the original compartment and saw me. luckily he didn't follow me and i quickly walked up the escalator. i experienced an aftershock the rest of the day as flashbacks of perverts rubbing on me or showing their weiners when i was a child came back to haunt me. i had to try hard to distract myself to get rid of the disgusting images in my head. focusing 100% during the ballet class really helped me dilute the impact of the shock. but i must say it wasn't an easy process for me. 
the fact that this event triggered such an emotional charge in me points to the fact that i had unhealed wounds from the past. what i went through as a child made me believe, falsely, that it was my fault to look attractive and cause those perverts to target me. for most of my teenage years, i deliberately tried to look very unattractive to avoid attention from men. during those years, i had no one to talk to safely about what i had experienced and so the trauma became internalized and never dealt with. worse still, the childhood traumas made me believe that only ugly guys or perverts were interested in me, deeply affecting my self-esteem and confidence as i grew up to be an adult. 
some of my friends have suggested calling the police or the mta officer yesterday. but i was in a very packed train and there were no mta officers onboard. besides, i was determined to get to my destination on time. but even if i had the time, how would i deal with the situation? drag the flasher to the mta booth? call the police? by the time the authorities arrive, the guy would have disappeared. i don't know. safety was at the top of my concern at that point, and i did not want any violent retaliation of any kind to happen to me. so even though i chose to be silent, it was out of self-preservation. tell me, what would you have done in such a situation? i don't have the vocab for calling out for help! #metoo

the fact that this event triggered such an emotional charge in me points to the fact that i had unhealed wounds from the past. what i went through as a child made me believe, falsely, that it was my fault to look attractive and cause those perves to target me. for most of my teenage years, i deliberately tried to look very unattractive to avoid attention from men. during those years, i had no one to talk to safely about what i had experienced and so the trauma became internalized and never dealt with. worse still, the childhood traumas made me believe that only ugly guys or perves were interested in me, deeply affecting my self-esteem and confidence as i grew up to be an adult. 
some of my friends have suggested calling the police or the mta officer yesterday. but i was in a very packed train and there were no mta officers onboard. besides, i was determined to get to my destination on time. but even if i had the time, how would i deal with the situation? drag the flasher to the mta booth? call the police? by the time the authorities arrive, the guy would have disappeared. i do not know. safety was at the top of my concern at that point, and i did not want any violent retaliation of any kind to happen to me. so even though i chose to be silent, it was out of self-preservation. tell me, what would you have done in such a situation? i do not have the vocab for calling out for help!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
『スーサイド・スクワッド』で大人気になったキャラ、マーゴット・ロビーが演じるハーレイ・クインは2019年に映画『birds of prey』で帰ってくることはすでに周知の事だが、これに続けとばかりに女性スーパーヒーロー物の映画・テレビ・配信シリーズが溢れている！

12月9日に、『オレンジ・イズ・ニュー・ブラック』のオーストラリア人女優ルビー・ローズがcwシリーズ『the flash/フラッシュ』でバットウーマンとしてデビューする。

2019年秋には元チアガール・女優ブレク・バッシンガーがdcユニバースの『stargirl』の実写版シリーズに主演。
同じくdcユニバース製作の『ハーレイ・クイン』アニメ版シリーズには、『ビッグバン★セオリー』ケイリー・クオコが主人公を演じる。

ハリウッドは『ハンガー・ゲーム』や『ワンダーウーマン』の成功の例から学んだように、#metooの時代には女性スーパーヒーローを押し出す戦略らしい。

全文はプロフィールにあるリンクから🔗

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
trigger warning 
excerpt from #metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women “since my first rape the summer before my freshman year of college i have had a repetitive thought in my head. i wish that they had killed me instead. “i wish that they had killed me instead.” because at least then it would have just been done and over with. i wouldn’t live with nightmares and ptsd and all the lifelong trauma that goes along with being raped. being sexually assaulted is that invasive and dehumanizing. like i said above, i’ve lost just about everything that made me who i was before the rapes. everything about me is different. i even laugh different. it’s basically like they killed me anyway. now i often feel just like a shell of a human being.”
.
.
my latest project is called “#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.”
i am still collecting stories. submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthor@yahoo.com.
all stories will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-sexual harassment -rape/assault -sexual, emotional, or physical abuse
-stalking
-gender discrimination
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing my own stories i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well along with the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.
.
.
#metoo #metoomovement #crimesagainstwomen #metoostory #truestories #truecrimes #shareyourstory #tellyourstory #ownyourstory #rapesurvivor #domesticviolence #abusiverelationship #ibelieveher #westandwithher

excerpt from  a collection of true story crimes against women “since my first rape the summer before my freshman year of college i have had a repetitive thought in my head. i wish that they had killed me instead. “i wish that they had killed me instead.” because at least then it would have just been done and over with. i wouldn’t live with nightmares and ptsd and all the lifelong trauma that goes along with being raped. being sexually assaulted is that invasive and dehumanizing. like i said above, i’ve lost just about everything that made me who i was before the rapes. everything about me is different. i even laugh different. it’s basically like they killed me anyway. now i often feel just like a shell of a human being.”
.
.
my latest project is called “ a collection of true story crimes against women.”
i am still collecting stories. submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthorahoo.com.
all stories will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-sexual harassment -rape/assault -sexual, emotional, or physical abuse
-stalking
-gender discrimination
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing my own stories i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well along with the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.
.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

if she wants to fuck you, she’ll want to fuck you the next time she sees you. it does not have to happen tonight. but in lieu of you actually managing to be patient for 3 days, there’s a very simple thing you can do to make sure she’s down:
.
ask her.
.

.
“i’m up for whatever you’re comfortable with.”
.
then as things get closer to actual sex… maybe she said to “get a condom,” maybe she’s you’re both naked and she’s sitting on top of you… just pause and say:
.
“are you sure you want to do this?”
.
if she says “no”, that’s ok! it doesn’t mean she never wants to! just look at her and say that’s totally fine, then go back to her place of comfort.
.
if she says “yes,” then go for it. enjoy! and if she isn’t understand that and take a step back. do you really want to be sleeping with someone who doesn’t want to be there?
.
this isn’t rocket science. but asking will earn trust. and trust builds chemistry. fucking when you have chemistry is an absolute game changer.
.
stay smart boys. it doesn’t take much and it makes the difference.
.

text:
i samband med #metoo under förra hösten gjorde vd:n för kungliga operan, birgitta svendén, ett flertal uttalanden om sexuella trakasserier. bland annat genom att slå fast att det på kungliga operan råder nolltolerans.
▪️
i maj i år dömdes en manlig operasångare för sexuellt ofredande av en 14-årig pojke. brottet begicks under hösten 2016 då mannen tafsade på den 14-årige pojkens könsorgan.
▪️
i samband med åtalet blev operasångaren arbetsbefriad, men är nu på väg tillbaka till kungliga operan.
▪️
”brottet begicks ju när personen inte var i tjänst och utanför operan som arbetsplats och därför så har vi som arbetsgivare både en skyldighet och ett ansvar att återinsätta personen i fråga” säger birgitta svendén.
▪️
eftersom brottet inte hände i tjänsten och för att påföljden blev en villkorlig dom med dagsböter så menar birgitta svendén att de inte har några juridiska möjligheter att avskeda personen.
▪️
foto: stina stjernkvist/tt

text:
how does empowerment mean going around semi nude and allowing people to objectify you? never heard that men come out naked to exert that they are strong or capable or talented... walking around, i noticed some young girls dressed skimpy and passerby men staring at them. this is a 'common' experience which you will hear from many people... so a quick question to all the women, why allow someone to treat you like an object? 
some have become so used to this that it no longer bothers them, but these are the ones who will do candle light march and a #metoo movement when they are actually not respecting themselves  learn to respect yourself and then expect others to respect you !!! leave your experience or thoughts below

text:
women should be aware of their surroundings and take action where required instead of hiding themselves from the prying eyes. men also have to start standing up and become disapproving of the bad behavior of other men.

don't be #chup. speak up. again and again.

to bring change in the society we first need to understand why these things happen. dr. deepa narayan has become a cultural detective to identify the root of these issues, to know more about her findings read her book 'chup: breaking the silence about india's women 👉 check the link in bio

text:
this morning i went out to breakfast with my mum before she went back home. it was soooo good 🤤

many of you will be a bit confused because my mum was over only recently.. (literally only a weeks ago) so i thought i’d address what has happened. not because i want attention but because i know a few people are wondering why i’ve fallen off social media lately.

last saturday night i went out clubbing and in the early hours of the morning i was sexually assaulted 😔 the police have been able to catch the man and he has confessed so it’s now in the hands of the court. 
i’m doing ok. my anxiety is back 100% which sucks. i was debating about opening up about this but with not having many people around me, social media is my go to for support. you guys have all supported me through my tough times post op so i thought i’d share this with you. 
to the girls who have already messaged me with support i want to say a huge thank you ❤️ i’m sorry if i’m not posting much or replying to messages at the moment. i just need some time to process what has happened and find some good coping strategies. 
if anyone has been though this or similar and you feel comfortable with talking to me please send me a message ❤️ #metoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

missed opportunities due to the language barrier.

text:
more details from saptamatrika... the 7 mothers. .
.
about mothers,sisters, daughters and friends- saptmatripa.
manifestations inspire me to attempt to analyze the world i see around me, 
especially as a woman who must make sense, daily 
of injustices in the world. 
to comprehend why we continue to look away when prejudice occurs, 
when sensitivities corrode, or when negative forces are invoked. 
i, therefore, look inwards 
to evoke the energy that is manifest in each one of us
to apply the healing salve of motherhood to a world that needs it. 
for that energy resides in each one of us 
women and men 
crossing all genders 
and it is that i must manifest..
.
.
.

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like ‘drain the swamp’ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the ‘deep state’ that weren’t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman
the independent

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

.

.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
a islândia é o país com a maior igualdade de gênero do mundo. na última semana, porém, a nação foi palco de um sórdido escândalo político que sugere que o sexismo é moeda corrente no interior do parlamento. um ex-premiê e vários outros legisladores foram captados numa gravação usando linguagem chula, grosseira e carregada sexualmente para descrever suas companheiras.
sigmundur david gunnlaugsson, um congressista da oposição que foi primeiro-ministro até ser expulso, supostamente por esconder a riqueza de sua família das autoridades fiscais, destacava-se entre as pessoas gravadas num bar, em frente ao parlamento de reykjavik, na tarde de 20 de novembro. ele estava na companhia do ex-ministro das relações exteriores gunnar bragi sveinsson, entre outros.
a gravação, realizada por um frequentador do bar, inclui legisladores do recentemente formado partido do centro e do partido do povo. pode-se escutar como o grupo zomba do movimento #metoo e compara um ex-parlamentar deficiente com um “animal”.
os vídeos, que rapidamente viralizaram na islândia, provocaram uma condenação generalizada em todo o país. durante a comemoração dos 100 anos de independência da dinamarca, neste sábado, foi realizada uma marcha de protesto contra os legisladores que protagonizaram o escândalo.
veja mais neste post!
fonte: el país 
#islândia #metoo #mulheres #sexismo #machismo #😤 #😡

text:
it is unlawful to discriminate against employees because of their sexual orientation. 
so how does sexual orientation discrimination appear in the workplace?

direct discrimination is where an employee is unfairly treated by their employer due to their sexual orientation or perceived sexual orientation. 
this includes:
opportunities for promotion and training
changes in employment terms and role responsibilities
differences in pay and benefits for individuals of different sexual orientation
redundancy and dismissal

direct discrimination also includes the recruitment process whereby job seekers are not offered a role based on their sexual orientation or perceived sexual orientation.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
next march, an employment tribunal will decide whether veganism is a "philosophical belief" protected by the equality act 2010.
what is defined as a ‘belief’?
this relates to both religious and philosophical belief. philosophical belief is a little trickier to define. it is not an opinion or point of view; rather it is identified under the equality act as genuinely held, clear, logical, convincing and a substantial aspect of human life and behaviour, worthy of respect in democratic society, compatible with human dignity and not conflicting with the fundamental rights of others – i said this was tricky!
humanism, atheism and agnosticism are examples of ‘beliefs’, but the key takeaway point here is we’re talking about a belief that is “not conflicting with the fundamental rights of others”.
it is also important to note that all protected beliefs are equal; no one belief carries more weight or influence over the other, nor does having no belief.
predictions on the outcome of this test case please....

what is defined as a ‘belief’?
this relates to both religious and philosophical belief. philosophical belief is a little trickier to define. it is not an opinion or point of view; rather it is identified under the equality act as genuinely held, clear, logical, convincing and a substantial aspect of human life and behaviour, wohy of respect in democratic society, compatible with human dignity and not conflicting with the fundamental rights of others – i said this was tricky!
humanism, atheism and agnosticism are examples of ‘beliefs’, but the key takeaway point here is we’re talking about a belief that is “not conflicting with the fundamental rights of others”.
it is also impoant to note that all protected beliefs are equal; no one belief carries more weight or influence over the other, nor does having no belief.

text:
perseverance
.
keep on going.
keep on fighting.
life is so damn fun and joyful but it can be intense and crazy too.
.
one of the greatest lessons that ironman training has taught me is that of perseverance. the road is long and the fight is sometimes difficult. but we must never ever give up.
.
i have a mantra i’ve always used during races when it gets tough...
.
“i didn’t come this far, to simply come this far.”
.
it’s carried me through the inevitable lows that we all experience racing. and even in moments when quitting seems like the “easy” option.
.
it’s paradoxical to me how much ironman training and races has paralleled my life the past 17 months. and especially now more than ever.
.
i didn’t come this far to come this far. doing the right, ethical and honest thing isn’t always easy. speaking about injustice whether experienced yourself or to others can be scary especially when silencing the victims, manipulation, threats and coercion run rampant in our society. telling the truth, speaking your truth and honoring the truth of those around has never been more vital.
.
i guess i never realized ironman training was actually preparing me for something bigger. giving me the mental and physical fortitude to step into the arena and not back down. i want to live in a society where women aren’t pushed down for speaking their truth and when they are met with betrayal, lies, threats, name calling and those who want them silenced...they persevere. i want to live in a world where i raise my boys to stand up for what’s right and be brave and courageous enough to stand up for women, their friends and themselves.
.
ironman has taught me the literal meaning of its slogan:
.
“anything is possible”
.
when you are walking in the truth, doors open. people enter your life to help and guide you. you have the strength of god, angels and the universe on your side. this i know for sure.
.
so persevere my friends. don’t quit. do the hard thing especially when it’s the right thing. you’ll sleep better at night knowing you’re speaking truth. keep on keeping on. life will throw you curve balls, highs and lows. ride them with grace. everything passes. love and truth alway wins 🖤🔥
name: Stephanie Rae 💋

text:
healing is a long process. i needed and still need time to heal myself. it's not like a broken bone that you simply wrap in plaster to heal the fracture and put the broken parts together again. you have to heal yourself and put your broken parts back together again by yourself.
the damage controlled me ever since. too afraid to talk about it, too afraid to go somewhere on my own, too many thoughts that i'm not good enough for anything or anyone. but i'm sick of being controlled.
so i started this page to talk about it. i booked flights and accomodation to go to a different country on my own. i keep on telling myself that i am indeed good enough and that people who don't value me can go and fuck themselves!
the damage doesn't control me any longer and you'll be able to get through this as well ♡
.
.

text:
there are hundreds of memes, viral videos, and challenges all over the internet. but through movements like body positivity, mental health awareness, and #metoo, social media has been able to truly impact lives, all over the world. herstory reached out to five young women who are using social media to empower themselves and others

1. arjama bakshi (@shareerspeak), 18, is a student from kolkata, is encouraging body positivity among teenagers and young adults through art and collaborations with other self-love advocates. she believes that we all should embrace our flaws and try our best to be authentically ourselves.

2. kavya shankar (@bodypositivecoach), 28, is a body-positive fitness entrepreneur from bengaluru, who has overcome challenges from body-shaming to sexual harassment. she shares her experiences with her followers, and has built a close-knit online family.

3. neelakshi singh (@plumptopretty), 27, is a body-positive fashion blogger from mumbai, who aims to destigmatise everything that challenges the standards of beauty. she is working towards the day when women's bodies are respected and not body-shamed.

4. leyre garatea (@leyleyleu), 27, is a spanish game designer living in bengaluru. she stands by and supports marginalised communities as much as she can, both online and off. she shares her own struggles with mental health and more, aiming to be as real as possible.

5. vijaya aswani (@spreefirit), 24, is an illustrator based in bengaluru, who hopes that her art makes people smile and feel better. she seeks support among women online, and looks up to those who voice their experiences out loud.

#socialmedia #empoweringwomen
#empowerment #empoweringgirls #bodypositive #bodypositivity #ngo #welfare #feminism #empowering #empoweringothers
